    <svcsubproc>
        <title>Cylinder Head Inspection - Valves Installed</title>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>Inspect cylinder head for thickness, warping, cracks, and valve leakage.</para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <figure id="f2650452" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd08/d0868.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="312px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Figure 132. Measurement of cylinder head thickness</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">To determine if cylinder head has been resurfaced, use a 3-4 inch micrometer to measure
                cylinder head deck thickness at four corner locations. If overall cylinder head thickness (deck-to-deck)
                specification is not met , install a new cylinder head.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f2650453" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd08/d0823.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="312px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Figure 133. Check for gasket surface flatness</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Feeler gauge</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Straightedge</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a Straightedge and Feeler Gauge to check cylinder head gasket surface for flatness. Use
                the following pattern. Check for flatness horizontally, diagonally, and transversely. If specifications
                are not met , install a new cylinder head.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f2650454" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd08/d0824.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="312px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Figure 134. Checking valve recession</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Straightedge</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Feeler gauge</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Valve head</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Before removing valves, check valve head recession (relative to deck) as follows:</para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Place a Straightedge across each valve.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Place a feeler gauge between Straightedge and valve head. Record valve recession
                    clearance.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">If out of specification , replace valve. Do step 2 again and if specifications are still
                    not met, install a new cylinder head.
                </para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Inspect for cracks in the cylinder head using the following dye penetrant method :</para>
            <figure>
                <graphic filename="../figd08/d0832.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="592px"/>
                <caption>Cleaner sprayed on cylinder head</caption>
            </figure>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Spray cleaner onto lower deck (gasket surface) of cylinder head and wipe dry.</para>
                <figure id="f2350426" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figd08/d0833.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
                    <caption>Figure 135. Spraying dye penetrant onto cylinder head</caption>
                </figure>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Spray dye penetrant onto lower deck (gasket surface) of cylinder head. Allow dye to
                    remain on surface from 1-30 minutes.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Wipe dye off cylinder head surface.</para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Dye will remain in any cracks during this 'wipe off' step.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Spray on developer and let dry for 5-15 minutes. Cracks will show up as purple lines
                    against white developer.
                </para>
                <figure id="f2350427" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figd08/d0888.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
                    <caption>Figure 136. Spraying developer onto cylinder head</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="f2350428" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figd08/d0835.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
                    <caption>Figure 137. Cylinder head crack between intake and exhaust valves</caption>
                </figure>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>To prevent engine damage, replace cylinder head, if cracked.</para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check for valve leakage using mineral spirits as follows:</para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Position cylinder head on wooden blocks with gasket surface facing down.</para>
                <figure id="f2650459" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figD08/D08186.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                             scalefitheight="312px" box="no"/>
                    <caption>Figure 138. Intake and exhaust ports sprayed with mineral spirits</caption>
                </figure>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Squirt mineral spirits into intake and exhaust ports.</para>
                <figure id="f2650460" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figd08/d0840.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                             scalefitheight="312px" box="no"/>
                    <caption>Figure 139. Leak inspection</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Inspection mirror</callout1>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Reflection of valve</callout1>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Flashlight</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Wait five minutes. Then use an inspection mirror to inspect valve seat area for leakage
                    of mineral spirits.
                </para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>Valve seats must not leak. Valve seat reconditioning is not required, if the cylinder head passes
                    the mineral spirits test. If valve seats leak, recondition the valves. See Removal in this section.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
    </svcsubproc>
